<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span></h2>
<div class="reflist" style="list-style-type: decimal;">
<div class="mw-references-wrap"><ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-13"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">"As a skilled craftsman makes a car, a singer I, Mighty One! this hymn for thee have fashioned. If thou, O Agni, God, accept it gladly, may we obtain thereby the heavenly Waters". – <i>Rigveda 5.2.11</i>, Translated by Ralph T.H. Griffith<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-23"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-23">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Elisa Freschi (2012): The Vedas are not <a href="/wiki/Deontological_ethics" title="Deontological ethics">deontic</a> authorities in absolute sense and may be disobeyed, but are recognized as a deontological <a href="/wiki/Epistemology" title="Epistemology">epistemic</a> authority by a Hindu orthodox school;<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup> (Note: This differentiation between epistemic and deontic authority is true for all Indian religions)</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-40"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-40">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The early Buddhist texts are also generally believed to be of oral tradition, with the first Pali Canon written many centuries after the death of the Buddha.<sup id="cite_ref-lopez1995p21_39-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lopez1995p21-39">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
</ol></div></div>
